C.push(capt("Table 4. Feature-group ablation (random forest, 5 seeds, mean ± s.d.)."));
C.push(H2("5.2 Calibrated uncertainty"));
C.push(P("Split-conformal intervals achieved 90.0% empirical coverage at the 90% nominal level, with a mean half-width of 1.50 percentage points of SOH, whereas the heuristic tree-quantile interval under-covered at 84.9%; the reliability diagram in Figure 3b shows that the conformal intervals track the ideal diagonal across all nominal levels while the tree-quantile heuristic under-covers throughout. The conformal interval thus provided better empirical calibration than the heuristic on this held-out split, which is a prerequisite for safety-relevant decision support, though not by itself sufficient for on-board deployment."));
fig("fig3_soh_panels.png", "Figure 3. SOH estimation on unseen cells (visualisation split, random forest). (a) Test-cell trajectories with 90% split-conformal prediction intervals; each cell is coloured individually and the legend reports its RMSPE. (b) Reliability diagram: observed versus nominal coverage for split-conformal and tree-quantile intervals against the ideal diagonal; (c) parity of predicted versus true SOH; (d) prediction-error distribution.", 620, 472).forEach(x => C.push(x));
C.push(H2("5.3 RUL prediction"));
C.push(P("Under the nominal-capacity EOL definition, 128 cells qualified, giving 15,046 cycle-level samples; the target RUL had a median of 337 cycles and ranged from 0 to 1933. To separate the deployable performance of RUL prediction from the optimism introduced by using measured SOH, we compared three input settings over five cell-level splits (Supplementary Table S2). A model using only the curve features, with no capacity label at inference, reached R² = 0.87 (MAE 65 cycles, 19% of the median RUL); supplying an out-of-sample SOH estimate gave R² = 0.82; and supplying the measured SOH as an oracle gave R² = 0.88 (MAE 59 cycles). The oracle therefore inflates performance only modestly, and a fully deployable model that needs no capacity measurement still predicts RUL with R² = 0.87. To reflect deployable performance rather than the oracle, the main RUL figure shows the end-to-end model, whose SOH input is an out-of-sample prediction (a SOH model trained on the training cells and applied to the held-out cells), not the measured capacity. On a single split this end-to-end model reached R² = 0.83 (MAE 74 cycles), and its 90% conformal intervals achieved 92.3% empirical coverage with a mean half-width of 203 cycles (Figure 4); the oracle trajectory using measured SOH (single-split R² = 0.90, MAE 50 cycles) is overlaid for comparison and is only modestly tighter, visually confirming that the deployable pipeline does not collapse when the measured label is withheld. Accuracy was strongly horizon-dependent: end-to-end MAE was 37 cycles for RUL below 100 cycles, rising to 130 cycles beyond 700, while the conformal half-width is fixed, so the intervals are widest relative to the error precisely near end-of-life; the same horizon dependence is illustrated for the SOH-assisted model in Supplementary Figure S4. In the SOH-assisted model the local degradation rate had the largest feature importance (0.67)."));
fig("rul_curves.png", "Figure 4. End-to-end RUL prediction on unseen test cells: the SOH input is an out-of-sample prediction, not the measured value. Blue points are the deployable end-to-end prediction with its 90% split-conformal interval (shaded); the black line is the true RUL trajectory (k_EOL - k); the grey dashed line is the oracle model using measured SOH, shown only for comparison.", 620, 333).forEach(x => C.push(x));
C.push(H2("5.4 Active-learning sample efficiency"));
C.push(P("On the homogeneous batches 1 and 2, uncertainty-based active learning and random sampling were indistinguishable within seed-to-seed variability across the labelling budget, with all differences well within one standard deviation over twelve seeds (Figure 5). At 39 revealed cells the two strategies reached R² = 0.71 ± 0.15 (active) and R² = 0.71 ± 0.13 (random), and random sampling was marginally ahead at most intermediate budgets. A single split can make active learning appear to win, but that apparent advantage did not survive seed averaging. The null result was robust to the initial seed size: increasing it from 6 to 12 to 18 cells left the two strategies indistinguishable in every case, with differences within one standard deviation (Supplementary Table S3). Uncertainty sampling therefore provided no reliable labelling-efficiency benefit here, a negative result that we interpret alongside the batch-effect findings in Section 6."));
fig("battery_learning_curve.png", "Figure 5. Active learning (uncertainty sampling) versus random sampling for cycle-life prediction on homogeneous cells (batches 1-2), mean ± s.d. over 12 seeds. The two strategies overlap within run-to-run variability (shaded ± s.d. bands) across the labelling budget.", 560, 368).forEach(x => C.push(x));
C.push(H2("5.5 Interpretable degradation law"));
C.push(P("Given 9 to 15 features, symbolic regression selected var(ΔQ) as the sole predictor on the pooled data. After a one-parameter linear calibration, the evolved expression log L = 0.96(-v_dQ + 1.99 - 2.72/v_dQ) + 0.21 reached a log-scale R² of 0.69 on the full pooled data (Figure 6, plotted in cycle-life units) and 0.63 on a held-out cell split, comparable to the hand-crafted variance model (0.65). Here v_dQ denotes the base-10 logarithm of the variance of ΔQ(V) between cycles 10 and 100; in our data it is of order -4, so the expression is not interpretable in raw physical units and the 1/v_dQ term stays well away from any singularity. When var(ΔQ) was offered among the candidate features, the search therefore reproduced the main empirical relationship reported by Severson et al. [1], rather than deriving it from first principles. On the homogeneous batches 1 and 2 it found a richer multi-feature expression reaching log-R² = 0.85, above the single-feature variance model (0.58). We emphasize that the symbolic-regression module identifies a known empirical relationship rather than deriving a novel physical law: the evolved expression contains a 1/v_dQ term with no clear physical meaning, and the result is best read as a compact data-fitting form. At the same time, the autonomous selection of var(ΔQ) from fifteen candidates demonstrates that data-driven structure search can automate a piece of feature engineering that originally required expert insight."));
fig("fig7_sr_parity.png", "Figure 6. Parity plot of the calibrated symbolic-regression formula versus true cycle life (pooled-data fit; the held-out-split result is reported in the text).", 380, 380).forEach(x => C.push(x));
C.push(H2("5.6 Cross-dataset validation and batch effects"));
C.push(P("Using the same feature-extraction and modelling protocol, we evaluated the framework on NASA under leave-one-cell-out (LOCO) validation. Ridge regression was the most accurate here, with a mean RMSPE of 2.48% and an overall R² of 0.955, ahead of the random forest (4.18%, R² = 0.875) and SVR (5.42%, R² = 0.789) (Table 5; Figure 7). This reversal of the Severson ranking suggests that simpler linear models can be more robust when very few cells are available, although, with only four cells, the NASA comparison is an initial indication of method applicability rather than a statistical conclusion, since a single anomalous cell could shift the ranking. Finally, although a batch-mixed 5-fold cross-validation gave R² = 0.80, training on batches 1 and 2 and testing on batch 3 collapsed to R² = -0.28, and testing on the 2019 batch to R² = -1.93. Naive pooling of heterogeneous batches therefore masked a severe cross-distribution failure that our cell-level and batch-aware protocols were designed to expose. The full 4-by-4 transfer matrix (Figure 8a) makes the pattern explicit: within-batch accuracy (diagonal, R² 0.46 to 0.74) coexists with erratic off-diagonal transfers ranging from R² = 0.49 down to -2.51, while the corresponding feature-distribution distances (Figure 8b) vary smoothly; the visual mismatch between the two panels anticipates the drift analysis of Section 6."));
fig("fig8_transfer_mmd.png", "Figure 8. Cross-batch transferability versus distribution distance. (a) Transfer R² for every train-test batch pair (diagonal: within-batch cell-level cross-validation); (b) maximum mean discrepancy (MMD) between batch feature distributions. The erratic transfer pattern in (a) contrasts with the smooth distance structure in (b), showing that input-distribution drift alone does not predict transfer success.", 620, 259).forEach(x => C.push(x));
C.push(table([3360, 2000, 2000, 2000], [
  ["Model (NASA, LOCO)", "Mean RMSPE (%)", "Overall R²", "Overall MAE (%)"],
  ["Ridge", "2.48", "0.955", "1.66"],
  ["SVR-RBF", "5.42", "0.789", "3.23"],
  ["Random forest", "4.18", "0.875", "2.56"],
]));
C.push(capt("Table 5. Second-dataset SOH on NASA under leave-one-cell-out (LOCO) validation. Mean RMSPE is averaged over the four held-out cells; overall R² and MAE are computed on the concatenated out-of-fold predictions."));
fig("nasa_soh_curves.png", "Figure 7. Second-dataset SOH on NASA under leave-one-cell-out validation: predicted versus true degradation for the four cells, shown for ridge regression, the best-performing model on NASA (Table 5); each panel title reports the per-cell RMSPE.", 600, 382).forEach(x => C.push(x));

C.push(H2("5.7 Partial voltage-window features for on-board deployment"));
C.push(P("Electric-vehicle battery management rarely observes a full charge or discharge cycle, and recent studies have shown that partial voltage segments suffice for SOH estimation [5,6,7]. Rather than claiming this observation as new, we verify that it holds within our framework, under strict cell-level splitting, and connect it to the IC-peak mechanism identified in Section 5.1. From each discharge curve we extracted the local IC peak, the capacity delivered in the window, and the median voltage within a voltage window of varying width and position, and re-trained the SOH model on these window features together with the summary HIs (Figure 9). A window covering only 10% of the voltage span, centred on the LFP phase-transition plateau, already reached R² = 0.90, against 0.94 for the full curve; a 20% window reached the same level, and accuracy then rose only gradually with width (Figure 9a). The window position was decisive. A 20% window centred on the plateau (3.1 to 3.3 V) gave R² = 0.90 to 0.92, whereas the same window placed in the low-voltage region (2.8 V) fell to 0.78 (Figure 9b). A practical guideline follows: an on-board SOH estimate of near-full-curve quality needs only a short voltage segment, provided that segment spans the phase-transition plateau where the incremental-capacity peak resides. The window need not be chosen by hand: consistent with the MI-guided selection of Javaid et al. [5] and Ren et al. [6], a scan that ranks candidate windows by the mutual information between their features and SOH automatically selects the plateau-adjacent region (MI peak at 3.1 V, accuracy peak at 3.0 V), in agreement with the heuristic choice (Supplementary Figure S5). Our scan is coarser than the 0.05 V segments of Ren et al. [6]; its purpose here is to tie the informative band to the IC-peak mechanism and to confirm the partial-window result under the cell-level and uncertainty-aware protocols of this framework, which the prior partial-segment studies do not address. We are deliberately careful about the scope of this result: the partial-window accuracy reported here is established within distribution (cell-level held-out cells of the same chemistry), and the adaptive-conformal calibration that keeps coverage near nominal under drift (Section 5.8) was demonstrated separately, on full-curve features under cross-batch streaming. The two are complementary deployability properties of the same framework rather than a single jointly validated result; the distribution-free nature of conformal calibration means it can in principle wrap a partial-window estimator and adapt its interval as the population drifts, but explicitly stress-testing a narrow-window model under cross-batch or cross-system drift, with adaptive conformal intervals, is a natural and important extension that we have not performed here and leave to future work."));
fig("supp_partial_window.png", "Figure 9. Partial voltage-window SOH estimation (random forest, five cell-level splits, mean ± s.d.). (a) SOH R² versus window width, with the window centred on the LFP plateau; a 10 to 20% window already approaches the full-curve accuracy. (b) SOH R² versus the centre voltage of a fixed 20% window; accuracy is high only when the window covers the phase-transition plateau (3.1 to 3.3 V, shaded).", 620, 238).forEach(x => C.push(x));
C.push(H2("5.8 Adaptive conformal inference under cross-batch drift"));
C.push(P("The split-conformal intervals of Section 5.2 assume exchangeability, which the cross-batch drift of Section 5.6 violates. We therefore streamed cells in batch order, with the point model trained and the interval calibrated only on the first batch, and compared three interval strategies that differ in the information they may use: static split-conformal (no updates after calibration), rolling recalibration (the same online residual stream as ACI, but a fixed α = 0.10), and adaptive conformal inference (ACI; [34]), which additionally adapts α from coverage feedback. The rolling baseline makes the comparison information-equal and separates the value of online data from the value of α-adaptation. Static conformal collapsed under the drift (8% coverage on the next batch, 36% overall against the 90% target). Rolling recalibration, with the same online information as ACI, recovered most of the loss (70 to 89% per batch, 82% overall, mean width 0.83 in log-life units). ACI closed the remaining gap, reaching 84 to 91% per batch and 89% overall, at the cost of wider intervals (mean width 1.07) (Figure 10). Most of the benefit therefore comes from online recalibration itself; the adaptive α contributes the final margin to near-nominal coverage. We also note an important caveat: because the underlying point model is itself degraded under this drift (Section 5.6), the calibrated intervals are wide. Conformal calibration keeps the uncertainty honest, correctly signalling that the model is out of its depth, but it does not restore the decision utility of an uninformative predictor; pairing online calibration with domain adaptation of the point model is the natural next step."));
fig("supp_aci.png", "Figure 10. Adaptive conformal inference under cross-batch drift, with an information-equal baseline. Cells are streamed in batch order with the model and calibration fixed on the first batch. (a) Static split-conformal (orange) collapses far below the nominal 90% (dashed); rolling recalibration with the same online residuals but fixed α (green) recovers most of the coverage; ACI (blue) reaches near-nominal by additionally adapting α. Rolling window of 25 cells. (b) Interval widths: static stays fixed, while the online methods widen honestly as residuals grow and narrow again on the closer batch 4.", 520, 403).forEach(x => C.push(x));
C.push(H2("5.9 Cross-system generalization (chemistry and protocol): direct LFP-to-LCO transfer"));
C.push(P("The cross-batch analysis (Section 5.6) showed that a model can fail on data drawn from a shifted distribution of the same chemistry. A stronger test is direct transfer across chemistries. We therefore trained the SOH model on the Severson LFP cells and applied it to an independent LCO dataset, the six prismatic CALCE CS2 cells (Section 3.1), parsed to 4,808 per-cycle discharge curves. Crucially, the two public datasets differ not only in cathode chemistry (LFP versus LCO) but also in charging protocol (multi-step fast-charging versus constant-current) and test temperature; this transfer therefore probes a combined, system-level shift, and the present design cannot attribute the outcome to chemistry alone (we return to this confound in Section 6). The chemistry difference is concrete at the feature level: the LCO incremental-capacity peak sits near 3.68 V, far from the 3.2 V LFP plateau on which the feature windows of Section 5.1 were defined, so absolute-voltage features computed on LFP have a different physical meaning on LCO. We compared four settings, all evaluated on held-out LCO cells (Table 6, Figure 11): (i) zero-shot, the frozen LFP-trained model applied to LCO; (ii) re-fit with native, data-driven feature windows, under cell-level splitting and multi-seed evaluation; (iii) re-fit while keeping the fixed LFP windows, to separate the effect of window placement from that of model transfer; and (iv) few-shot re-fitting on a small number N of labelled LCO cells."));
C.push(P("The result is unambiguous and graded. The frozen LFP model does not transfer: zero-shot SOH reaches only R² = 0.06 (RMSPE 15.6%), predicting close to a constant value regardless of true SOH (Figure 11c). Re-fitting the same pipeline on LCO recovers most of the performance (R² = 0.90 ± 0.06, RMSPE 4.5%), and its split-conformal intervals, calibrated on a held-out LCO cell, reach 89% empirical coverage at the 90% level. Adaptation is inexpensive: a single labelled LCO cell already lifts R² to 0.84, and three cells to 0.85 (Figure 11b). Re-fitting with the original LFP windows performs as well as with native windows (R² = 0.89 versus 0.90), which localizes the cause: it is the trained model, not the feature definition, that fails to cross chemistries; once the model is re-fit on the target chemistry, even imperfectly placed feature windows carry enough degradation signal for a tree ensemble to relearn the mapping. This refines our initial expectation that window mislocation would dominate the failure."));
C.push(P("This is the honest reading of framework universality. A single trained model is chemistry-specific and should not be claimed to transfer zero-shot; what transfers is the methodology, namely the feature pipeline together with the cell-level and conformal protocols, which re-targets to a new chemistry with a small, quantified labelling budget. The pattern is consistent with the cross-batch collapse of Section 5.6: both are concept-drift failures of a fixed feature-to-life mapping, here across a combined chemistry-and-protocol (system-level) change rather than across a manufacturing batch. Two limits should be stated plainly. First, only six LCO cells were available, so the LCO error bars are wider and its RMSPE (4.5%) is higher than on LFP (1.26%). Second, the conformal calibration is itself small-sample-limited, and we quantified this directly with a calibration-cell sweep (Table 6): with a single calibration cell the empirical coverage is unstable (83 ± 8% across seeds), it recovers toward the 90% target with two cells (88 ± 4%, with a tighter spread), and three calibration cells over-cover (95 ± 2%) at the cost of starving the fit (R² falls from 0.93 to 0.78). Increasing the calibration set therefore does restore coverage from the degenerate single-cell case, but with only six cells it trades against fitting data; both limits are consequences of small N, not of the method, and neither affects the central, deliberately falsifiable finding, that zero-shot fails and re-fit recovers, which would have been equally reportable had re-fitting also failed."));
C.push(table([3360, 1500, 1620, 2280], [
  ["Setting (LCO target, held-out cells)", "R²", "RMSPE (%)", "Conformal coverage"],
  ["Zero-shot (frozen LFP model)", "0.06", "15.6", "n/a"],
  ["Re-fit (LFP feature window)", "0.89", "4.5", "91%"],
  ["Re-fit (native feature window)", "0.90", "4.5", "89%"],
  ["Few-shot, 1 labelled LCO cell", "0.84", "6.5", "21% (degenerate)"],
  ["Few-shot, 3 labelled LCO cells", "0.85", "5.8", "71%"],
  ["Calibration sweep, 1 calibration cell", "0.93", "—", "83 ± 8%"],
  ["Calibration sweep, 2 calibration cells", "0.92", "—", "88 ± 4%"],
  ["Calibration sweep, 3 calibration cells", "0.78", "—", "95 ± 2%"],
]));
C.push(capt("Table 6. Direct cross-system (LFP-to-LCO) transfer and small-sample conformal calibration (CALCE CS2). R² and RMSPE are on held-out LCO cells; re-fit and few-shot values are means over five cell-level splits. Zero-shot uses the frozen LFP model with no LCO labels. Conformal coverage is at the 90% nominal level with cell-level calibration. Few-shot coverage is reported despite small-calibration degeneracy (one calibration cell gives unreliable coverage). The calibration sweep (two held-out test cells, eight seeds) isolates the calibration-set size: coverage recovers from the unstable single-cell case (83 ± 8%) toward nominal with two cells (88 ± 4%), while dedicating three of the six cells to calibration over-covers (95 ± 2%) and starves the fit (R² 0.93 to 0.78), making the small-sample trade-off explicit. RMSPE is not reported for the sweep, which varies the calibration partition rather than the model."));
fig("crosschem_result.png", "Figure 11. Direct cross-system transfer (chemistry and protocol), LFP to LCO (CALCE CS2). (a) SOH R² on held-out LCO cells: the frozen LFP model collapses (red) while re-fitting the pipeline on LCO recovers, with native and LFP feature windows tying. (b) Adaptation budget: R² versus the number of labelled LCO cells, against the full re-fit (dashed) and zero-shot (dotted) references; even one cell recovers most of the gap. (c) Predicted versus true SOH for a held-out LCO cell (CS2_38): zero-shot predictions collapse to a near-constant band, whereas the re-fit model tracks the diagonal.", 620, 190).forEach(x => C.push(x));
C.push(H1("6. Discussion"));
C.push(P("Interpretability and the role of IC features. The ablation and the feature-importance analysis together support a physically plausible interpretation of the model. Summary indicators alone are weak (R² = 0.65); the shape of the discharge voltage curve carries most of the signal (R² = 0.92); and IC descriptors refine it further (R² = 0.93), with the IC peak height accounting for 0.88 of the random-forest importance. This pattern is consistent with the electrochemistry, since loss of active material and of lithium inventory both attenuate and shift the LFP phase-transition peak ([35,36]; Figure 2). The symbolic-regression result points the same way: given fifteen candidate features, the search selected var(ΔQ) and recovered a known empirical degradation relationship when that feature was present, rather than deriving it from first principles."));
C.push(P("Why calibrated uncertainty matters. Our point accuracy (RMSPE 1.26 ± 0.26%) is competitive with the literature, but the more deployment-relevant property is interval calibration. Split-conformal intervals reached 90.0% empirical coverage at the 90% level, against 84.9% for an uncalibrated heuristic. For battery-management decision support, calibrated prediction intervals are preferable to uncalibrated point estimates, but additional validation under on-board sensing and pack-level conditions is still required before deployment, even though the partial-window analysis (Section 5.7) already indicates robustness to incomplete cycles."));
C.push(P("Active learning did not provide a reliable benefit. On homogeneous data, uncertainty sampling matched random sampling once results were averaged over twelve seeds, and a single split could create a misleading impression of superiority (Figure 5). We diagnosed this null result (Supplementary Table S4). The random-forest and Gaussian-process uncertainty estimates correlated only weakly with the actual prediction error (Spearman 0.37 and 0.24), and replacing the random forest with a Gaussian-process surrogate [37], whose uncertainty is in principle better calibrated, did not recover an advantage (R² = 0.73 ± 0.20 against 0.69 ± 0.18 for random sampling). Because changing the model does not help, the failure is most consistent with pool homogeneity: on these similar cells, informativeness varies too little for any acquisition rule to exploit, which also explains the weak uncertainty-error correlation. This null result is a useful counterpoint to the common assumption that uncertainty sampling is always preferable, and it reinforces the broader theme that apparent gains must be checked against seed and split variation. We note the converse possibility: on genuinely heterogeneous fleet data, where informativeness varies widely across cells, acquisition rules that reward diversity or representativeness rather than raw uncertainty may yet deliver the labelling-efficiency gains that were absent here; comparing them is a natural follow-up."));
C.push(P("Batch effects as a hidden hazard. The gap between a batch-mixed cross-validation (R² = 0.80) and genuine cross-batch transfer (R² from -0.28 to -1.93) is the most cautionary result. A model that looks excellent under random splitting can fail completely on a new batch or chemistry. This motivates our consistent use of cell-level and batch-aware evaluation, and it echoes the small-data NASA result, where the simplest model generalised best. Reporting protocols should therefore state the train and test partitioning explicitly, because that choice silently determines whether a reported accuracy reflects deployable performance. To probe the cause, we measured the input-feature distribution distance between batches with the radial-basis-function maximum mean discrepancy (MMD; [38]). MMD correlated only weakly with single-batch transfer R² (Spearman 0.30), and no MMD threshold cleanly separated successful from failed transfers (Figure 8; scatter view in Supplementary Figure S2). Covariate shift alone therefore does not explain the collapse. The remaining candidates are concept drift, that is, a shift in the feature-to-life mapping between charging-policy families, a shift in the label distribution itself (batch cycle lives differ systematically; Supplementary Figure S6), and the instability of single-batch training on roughly forty cells; these appear to contribute more than input-distribution drift alone, possibly compounded by batch-to-batch differences in charging protocol. This argues for label-aware domain adaptation rather than input-distribution matching alone [39], which is left to future work. Crucially, this collapse and the active-learning null result of Section 5.4 are two faces of the same underlying limitation rather than isolated negatives. The within-batch homogeneity that we identified as the reason uncertainty sampling cannot outperform random selection, because informativeness varies too little across near-identical cells, simultaneously means that a model trained within one batch sees a narrow slice of the population and has little pressure to learn features that remain valid outside it. A pool that is too homogeneous for acquisition to exploit is, by the same token, too homogeneous to train a model that survives the distribution shift of a new batch or chemistry. Read together, the two diagnostics describe a single mechanism: a single batch under-samples the operating population that a deployed model must serve, which is precisely why both within-batch acquisition gains and cross-batch transfer fail, and why genuine progress requires more diverse training data or explicit domain adaptation rather than a cleverer acquisition rule on a homogeneous pool."));
C.push(P("Alternative explanations and failure modes. Several findings admit more than one reading. The dominance of the IC peak may partly reflect the sharp LFP phase-transition plateau rather than a universal property of SOH, so the feature ranking could differ for other chemistries. The absence of an active-learning gain may stem from miscalibrated small-sample uncertainty as much as from genuine pool homogeneity. The strong NASA performance of ridge regression rests on only four cells and noisy capacity labels, so it should be read as suggestive rather than conclusive. Finally, the conservative coverage of the RUL intervals likely reflects residual heteroscedasticity across prediction horizons, which Supplementary Figure S4 makes explicit: absolute errors grow several-fold from short to long horizons while the conformal half-width is constant."));
C.push(P("Limitations. Our point accuracy does not yet match the 0.45% RMSPE of Roman et al. [12], who use thirty features and adversarial augmentation; closing this gap is left to future work. The NASA validation, although standard, involves only four cells. Direct cross-chemistry transfer (Section 5.9) confirms that a frozen model does not cross chemistries and must be re-fit on the target; this re-fit was demonstrated on only six LCO cells, so the LCO error bars are wide and a larger multi-chemistry study is needed to map the adaptation budget precisely. A further open question is to disentangle chemistry shift from operating-condition shift (temperature, depth-of-discharge and C-rate), which would require a dataset that varies both axes within a common protocol, such as the Sandia multi-chemistry cycling corpus; its complete per-step time series is not openly downloadable and must be requested from the data provider, so this separation is left to future work. We also did not benchmark recurrent or Transformer models on raw cycle sequences [32,33]; a multilayer perceptron on the tabular features was unstable at this cell count (Section 5.1), and temporal deep models, which typically require more cells, are a natural extension once larger datasets are pooled. Finally, RUL accuracy remains horizon-dependent, with larger errors far from end-of-life."));

C.push(H1("7. Conclusion"));
C.push(P("We presented an interpretable and uncertainty-aware framework for lithium-ion battery SOH and RUL prognostics and evaluated it under strict cell-level protocols on two public datasets spanning two chemistries. Using only charge and discharge curve features, with a single incremental-capacity descriptor carrying most of the SOH model importance, the framework estimated SOH at RMSPE 1.26 ± 0.26% (R² = 0.933 ± 0.03 over five cell-level splits) and RUL at R² = 0.87 from curve features alone, needing no capacity label at inference (R² = 0.88 with measured SOH as an oracle upper bound). Its split-conformal intervals are empirically calibrated and, in an adaptive form, remain near nominal coverage under cross-batch drift where static conformal collapses, and symbolic regression reproduced an interpretable degradation law. A partial voltage window of only 10 to 20%, spanning the phase-transition plateau, retained near-full SOH accuracy, indicating compatibility with the partial cycles seen in real operation. Equally important, rigorous evaluation exposed two failure modes that single-split studies can hide: uncertainty-based active learning did not reliably beat random sampling, and naive cross-batch transfer collapsed, whereas the same protocol remained effective on NASA under leave-one-cell-out validation. A direct LFP-to-LCO transfer test made the scope of this generalisation explicit: a frozen model collapses under the combined chemistry-and-protocol shift (R² = 0.06) while the re-fitted pipeline recovers (R² = 0.90, 89% coverage) from as little as one labelled target cell, indicating that it is the methodology rather than a single trained model that transfers. Within the evaluated datasets and protocols, the framework therefore offers accurate, calibrated and interpretable prediction, while the cross-batch tests show that random cell-level cross-validation can overstate deployable performance. Future work will add partial-cycle and charge-segment features, study weighted or group-conformal intervals and conformalised quantile regression for the horizon-dependent RUL errors [40,41,42], and pursue label-aware domain adaptation and physics-informed machine learning to close the cross-batch and cross-chemistry gaps identified here."));

C.push(H1("Supplementary Information"));
fig("supp_permutation_importance.png", "Supplementary Figure S1. SOH feature permutation importance on held-out cells (decrease in test R² after permuting each feature, five seeds, mean ± s.d.). Permuting the IC peak feature reduces the test R² by 0.94, far more than any other feature, confirming the impurity-based ranking in the main text.", 480, 377).forEach(x => C.push(x));
